d to structural similarities that arise out of the characteristic way in which the people of a certain epoch see and memorize facts aesthetically. Mnemosyne, at once the goddess of memory and the mother of the muses, presides over this view of the arts. In illustrating her influence, Praz ranges widely through Western sources, providing an incomparable tour of the literary and pictorial arts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics. 0aArt and literature. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAlexandrians.  aAthens.  aCanova, Antonio.  aD’Annunzio, Gabriele.  aForster, E. M.  aFoscolo, Ugo: Grazie.  aGiorgione.  aHagstrum, Jean H.  aHomer.  aHorace: Ars poetica.  aJames I, king of England.  aJonson, Ben.  aKeats, John.  aLouis XIV, king of France.  aMartin, John.  aPhilostratus the Elder.  aPico della Mirandola, Giovanni.  aPlutarch.  aPoussin, Nicolas.  aPre-Raphaelites.  aRome: Imperial.  aSimonides of Ceos.  aVasari, Giorgio.  aWind, Edgar.  ahieroglyphics.  apainting and poetry, correspondence between.  apoetry, Japanese.  asphinx.  atechnopaignia.  aut pictura poesis.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691252193?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691252193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691252193/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles